elements.summary: Roxi is a regenerative artivist, protopian futurist, ontological designer, experiential producer, transdisciplinary social sculptor and creative doula. Her quest is to harness this intersectional approach to catalyze social and systemic change through inclusive, transdisciplinary collaborations for the regeneration of our planet and culture. Her path is grounded in a commitment to creating inspiring and embodied ways of learning together. As behavior is a function of culture - she supports and develops creative cultural interventions and co-learning evolutionary containers. Her thesis is rooted in a belief that as we perpetuate equitable and just cultures, societal behaviors participating in life affirming ways of being will emerge in that process. As we are facing a crisis of imagination, Roxi’s efforts encourage collective imagination beyond the limits of the plausible and probable into the possible in service to the potential of a world where all life thrives at the expense of none. She is a deep believer and practitioner in designing for states of being, having those states of being prime us for connection, reparations and regeneration with ourselves, each other and our beautiful living planet.

elements.summary: Taiyo Okamoto reimagines the traditional Japanese technique of chigiri-e to deconstruct and layer painted and textured paper into contemplative abstract patterns. Liberating the true self is his universal theme. What happens when we remove and let go of the heavy armors of identity and anxiety, and return to our unshakeable axis? Process becomes meditation; each paper sculpture a concrescence of time and the artist’s vital essence. Working across mediums, explorations of color theory, material-driven composition, the nature of water and documenting the transformation of his own body have led to several painting and photography series, as well as a digital fashion collaboration with the design team NauGhTed, that consider many of the same practices. Everything becomes an experiment in transmuting a tender reality. Taiyo Okamoto grew up by the ocean in Karatsu, Japan, where he often spent his childhood days twilighting on the seawall; dreamily gazing at the vast sky, crashing waves, and flying fish. He has lived in New York City since 2002. Taiyo’s art has featured in exhibitions in New York, London and Taipei. He appears in the film "HANAGATAMI" directed by legendary Japanese filmmaker Nobuhiko Obayashi.

elements.description:
Regenerate yourself. 

Trying to change the world without first changing ourselves is perhaps arrogance. However when we give permission to ourselves to change, everything changes.

But in order to do so, it is necessary to know ourselves first. 

Being influenced by the mainstream worldview, many of us might have forgotten who we really are. 

What is our true nature? 

Rediscover it and listen carefully to its whisper. 

In the process, the harmony within ourselves will be effortlessly realized in this world. 

This is multidisciplinary artist Taiyo Okamoto’s short animation experiment which embodies that philosophy. 

This is a collaboration piece with the (r)Evolutionaries of Pod 11 as well.

elements.description:
In this immersive workshop, participants dive into the transformative world of Theatre of the Oppressed. We begin by tracing the rich history of this theatrical approach, exploring its roots in social activism and its evolution into a powerful tool for societal change.


Through a series of engaging Theatre of the Oppressed games and exercises, participants experience firsthand the potential of this approach to break down barriers and foster empathy, understanding, and dialogue. These interactive activities are designed to empower voices, challenge assumptions, and promote critical thinking.


Following the experiential session, we come together for an integration session where participants reflect on their experiences, share insights, and discuss practical applications of Theatre of the Oppressed in everyday life and within broader societal contexts.


Join us in this journey of exploration and discovery, where we harness the power of theatre to inspire change, foster inclusivity, and amplify diverse voices.
elements.label: Voices Unleashed: Theatre of the Oppressed in Action

elements.summary: Join us in Tuning to Nature with Stefanie Atkinson Schwartz's unique perspective inspiring wonder and connection through phenomenological exploration.
elements.description:
"Tuning to Nature: A Phenomenological Perspective" invites viewers on an immersive journey through a series of dynamic photographic projections. Photographer Stefanie Atkinson Schwartz shares her unique perspective, capturing unseen wonders and revealing the intricate beauty of the natural world. 


As viewers delve into each photograph, they're encouraged to embrace a sense of wonder and curiosity, allowing themselves to fully immerse in the present moment.


 Phenomenology is a philosophical approach that emphasizes the study of conscious experience and the structures of perception. When applied to nature, it encourages us to immerse ourselves fully in the present moment and to be receptive to the rich sensory input that nature offers. 


One aspect of this approach is cultivating what the philosopher Martin Heidegger called "being-in-the-world." This concept suggests that we  not isolated observers of nature but intimately connected to it, and our experiences of the world are inseparable from our existence within it. 


By embracing this interconnectedness, we can deepen our appreciation for the natural environment and develop a sense of belonging within it. Phenomenology also involves suspending judgment and allowing ourselves to experience nature as it is, without imposing labels or categories. This means approaching nature with a sense of openness and wonder, allowing each moment to unfold organically and revealing its unique qualities. By doing so, we can cultivate a more authentic and immediate connection with the natural world, free from the constraints of conceptual thinking.
elements.label: Tuning to and Focusing upon Nature from a phenomenological perspective.

elements.summary: Portal to the New Earth: Sound, Sacred Geometry & Grid Enegries for Personal & Planetary Transformation
elements.description:
A detailed explanation of three-dimensional sacred geometry and how it relates to the evolution of human consciousness, the Earth's energy body and the whole universe - starting with the golden ratio and the five platonic solids, it progresses through their multiple inter-relationships all the way to the 64 tetrahedron “Structure of the Vacuum” grid, discovered by the physicist Nassim Haramein.

 

I show how the Portal installations, built for Burning Man and festivals around the world since 2004, utilize sacred geometry, Earth energies and sound vibrations to harmonize participant’s multidimensional vibrational energy body with the evolution of the Earth’s geometric grid to facilitate an evolution of consciousness.

 

The intention of the Portal installations is to awaken people to choose to create and live in ecologically sustainable habitations. I present a history of visionary architecture and city designs that are integrated with nature to create a world of sacred beauty. Culminating with an original design process called "TerrAquaForming”: shaping the earth and water into dense regenerative living ecosystems for human habitation to exist in harmony with all life and the Earth.

 

The ultimate purpose of this presentation is to inspire participants to envision and create these future environments together synergetically.
elements.label: Portal to the New Earth: Sound, Sacred Geometry & Grid Enegries for Personal & Planetary Transformation

elements.summary: This workshop will explore the insights and integration of the arts and sciences as valuable tools for addressing society's most pressing challenges.
elements.description:
For most of human history, art and science have been entangled tools for understanding ourselves and the world. Our early discoveries and possibilities were driven by both creativity and experiment, imagination and invention. Since the rise of university siloes, specialization, and mythical divisions like "left-brained" or "right-brained" people, we've seen the arts and sciences become artificially opposed and forced apart by schools, social circles, and constructed ways of being.


In this workshop, we'll explore the interplay of art and science as practical tools for changemakers and movements. We'll consider both the points of overlap and distinct offerings of these spheres, considering case studies on how our epistemological vantage points inform our collective strategies and realities. We'll engage with guiding insights on human change and openness from the fields of neuroscience and psychology, as well as how they may be strengthened by the wisdoms of storytellers, musicians, artists, and designers.


Our goal is to pursue the reintegration of our curious and creative selves, so that we may apply the full power of human inquiry and imagination to address the most daunting and civically-critical challenges of our time.
elements.label: The Art & Science of Driving Change

elements.description:
Disaster is on the rise, and communities on the front lines need support. With global displacement set to rise from one in 68 people today to one and seven over the next 30 years. United Refuge is here to help! Founded by collective of humanitarian actors, we, deploy teams into disaster areas to help community based organizations rise to demands of complex humanitarian responses and the pathway to recovery. 

Our unique Think/Do approach and Community Based org Incubator fast track the support to local orgs ensuring their leadership guides recovery. 

Today we will share our work with Damour for community development. A Palestinian NGO founded In 2010 and focused social and environmental projects in Gaza and the west bank. 

In the months following the devastating assault from Hamas on OCT 7, and the ongoing hostage situation. Gazas civilians have born the majority of the conflicts destruction. With the displacement of nearly 2.5 million people and the destruction of 85% of the infrastructure.  

Damour co-founder Tahani Abu Daqqa, seeing the great need, helped to build 3 camps to support displaced Gazans and is now building a 4th. 

Over the last 2 months, in deep collaboration Damour, UR and our partners have started building one roadmap for a sustainable, locally led emergency response and potential pathways to a more peaceful future. 

In this brief presentation we will take a look at local efforts to date and what we see coming!

elements.summary:
Exhibit 1: Tuscon Arroyo Wash Reclamation Desert Biome Ecosystem. 

An immersive experience into the desert biome of Tuscon Arizona, where an arroyo was imaginatively unearthed to create a village based on the indigenous flora and fauna where food scapes, wellness, and community intersect with ecological systems that steward the natural cycles. 

Exhibit 2: IndigiFutures, A Mexica Cityscape ReImagined as A Solar Teocalli.

A cityscape based on the indigenous teachings of being stewards to our planet, of being in connection to the sun, of building our structures in harmony with creation. Uplifitng the teocalli design and reframing it as a modern city building in the middle of a future metropolis centered on Mexica building principles. 

Exhibite 3: Honoring and Holding Space for Water as Our Relative and the Hands that Feed Us, a Waterpark immersive playground 

Based on the genius of Mario Schjetnan, an imaginary water-based community space was envisioned to honor the hands that feed us; the farmer workers who's lives are intricately intertwined with our food, our ecological systems, and the collective liberation of us all. 

Overarching Theme: Water as a connector, as a reservoir for our collective healing. We remember the other great lakes of the south: Lake Zumpango, Lake Xaltocan, Lake Texcoco, Lake Xochimilco, Lake Chalco
elements.label: Cityscapes and Indigenous Planning Reclamation and Food-Eco Systems

elements.summary:
Words aren't the thing. They are, however, the thing that gets us to the thing. At least, they have that potential. 

But there are other vocabularies of communing with ourselves, with the other beings around us, with the world. Such as walking. And other forms of moving ones body through space and time. Because we all have different capacities and relationships with walking, I like to think of the core element is moving oneself through space and time. Or perhaps, more succinctly, it's about embodying change.

I am slowly gestating a series of time-based visual appetizers, if you will. Something tells me there is a full course meal to be birthed from these. In the meantime, I am grateful for the opportunity of this exhibition to help motivate me to make substantive progress toward curating a small selection of these short video clips from my personal archives.
elements.label: Portals of Possibility: A Vocabulary

Alixa García is a distinguished artist, visionary thinker, published author, social and environmental justice leader, and organizational strategist. Her groundbreaking work with Climbing Potree set the tone for years of art for movement building that has had significant ripple effects throughout the world.

Her unique approach centralizes art for movement building and the role of imagination as an essential tool for liberation. 

Alixa is a sought-after keynote, public speaker, visual artist, and trainer. Her work has been published by Whit Press, AK Press, Hatchett, & Daraja Press. Her latest offering, a Course on the Imaginal: Cultivating the Visionary Self, is built on 16 years of work exploring the imaginal space, somatic abolition, biomimicry, intersectionality, creativity and love as the ultimate context.

elements.summary: I am working on a constellation of projects that orbit around the concept of distributed manufacturing. Distributed manufacturing is a reimagination of how we make things where we no longer have highly extractive centralized factories, but rather bring the production equipment as close as possible to the natural resources and the market. This will bring production equipment closer to the natural resources and the market to create a regenerative closed loop within that biosphere. Meaning you grow things and you process them to make products and then return the excess to enrich the ecosystem. With an increase in biodiversity and increase in value and generally an improvement of the capacity of the local economy is improved.

But what does an alternate climate resilient set of futures look like? What is the future we desire?
